e to further his career and invented the portrait of Spenser as his admiring disciple. Contextualising Spenser’s life by comparisons with Shakespeare and Sir Walter Ralegh, Brink shows that Spenser shared with Sir Philip Sidney an allegiance to the early modern chivalric code. His departure for Ireland was a high point, not an exile.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aShakespeare 2019. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Modern / 16th Century .2bisacsh  aAlexander Nowell.  aEdmund Spenser.  aElizabethan court.  aPhilip Sydney.  aWalter Ralegh.  achivalry.1 aBrink, Jean R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2019 eBook-Packagez978311128249740uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152614259740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526142597423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526142597/original  a978-3-11-128249-7  Manchester University Press 2019 eBook-Packageb2019  aGBV-deGruyter-alles